Consumer Expenditure Pattern Analysis¶

Author: Xiyuan Wu & Tiannan Yang¶

To Change Whose Mind About What¶

We are trying to let scientists doing similar researches to ours believe that our results are credible and robust.

We also hope that companies can avoid stereotype and correctly make their decisions based on our findings.

Introduction¶

To acheive the above goal, this project analyzes the expenditure patterns of various consumer units using national consumer expenditre data. We are aiming at finding the similarities and differences between groups and where these deviances come from.

We use machine learning techniques like K-Means Principal Component Analysis (PCA) for visualization of distinct consumer unit clusters. We also conduct within cluster analysis to achieve our goals by showing corresponding graphs. Finally, Multinomial Logistic Regression is performed to see how household characteristics affect consumer expenditre patters.

Database¶

The Consumer Expenditure Survey public-use microdata (PUMD) http://www.bls.gov/cex/pumdhome.htm

2012 Quarterly Interview Survey data

Variables selection:

Expenditure variable: Food, Housing , Transportation etc 
Household Characteristics
   Discrete: Number of Earners etc.
   Categorical: Age of Reference, Race of Reference etc

All files related to this project are available on GitHub: https://github.com/zoewu/project and https://github.com/tyang9010/Project

1. Data Preparation¶

Variables are divided into two categories: the expenditure variables and the household characteristics variables. For expenditure variables, percentages are used instead of the actual amount so it is comparable between different groups. Another advantage of percentages is to represent the contributions of expenditures for each group. Also the quarterly data are cleaned and annualized before usage. For the household characteristics variables, they are separated into continuous variables (i.e, Number of Earners) and categorical variables (i.e, Age of Reference Person). Some of the categorical variables are recoded to be more interpretable.

2. Data Analysis and Visualization¶

2.1 Clustering by Expenditure¶

First or the most important step of data analysis is to identify the different consumer unit groups. The K-Means result is plotted by the projecting the original data onto the plane spanned by the first two principal components from PCA. According to the results of several visualizations, the number of clusters is chosen to be three which performed the best. Notice that the PCA graphs may differ slightly across replications due to the unstable assignments of the first two principal components.

In [10]:
In [11]:

Figure 2. Boxplots for three typical types of expenditures

Three boxplots of food, housing and transportation expenditures are used to investigate the different characteristics of these three groups. The group with the highest mean food expenditure percentage is labeled as “Food Dominant”. The same reasoning can be applied to “Housing Dominant” and “Transportation Dominant”.

2.2 Cluster Profile Analysis¶

Here the household characteristics among different clusters are analyzed using the CU characteristic data.Basicly we are trying to get a qualitative sense of CU characteristics within and between groups. Although exact percentage can be obtained from our code, it does not provide much help to the project topic or for display purposes.

In [64]:

Figure 3. Bar chart for categorical variables

Age of Reference Person: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of reference person's age of each cluster.Not much difference can be found here.

Race of Reference Person: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of reference person's race of each cluster. The majority of all three groups are white people. Racial compositions are slightly different between groups.

Highest Level of Education within the Household: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of highest education levels completed of each cluster. Not much difference can be found here.

Urban/Rural: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of people living in urban and in the suburb of each cluster. The majority of all three groups are living in urban. However, there are more families living in the urban area falling into the Housing Dominant group.

Housing Tenure: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of housing tenures of each cluster. Most families in the Housing Dominant group are renting houses, while the other two groups have similar patterns for housing tenures.

Income Class of CU Based on Income before Taxes: Stacked bar chart for the percentage split of income class of households based on income before taxes of each cluster. The Housing dominant goup has slightly overall lower income than the other two groups.

In [17]:

Figure 4. Bar chart for discreet variables

The above are bar chart comparisons of discrete household characteristics variables for the three clusters. Most of them display similar within-group characteristics except for number of earners. Households in the Housing Dominant group tend to have fewer earners than the other two groups.

2.3 Multinomial Logistic Regression Analysis¶

Multinomial Logisitc Regression is performed to evaluate which characteristic variables have what effects on a certain household, or say, what factors make a certain household fall into one of the three clusters.

The first table displays the regression coefficients.

The second table displays the marginal effects of all predictors.

The third table displays the comparison of marginal effects between three groups.

It is more straightforward to display the results in terms of marginal effect.

To interpret the table above, we mainly look at the "dy/dx" column. A positive number means that one unit increment of the predictor increases the probability of the household falling into that group by the corresponding "dy/dx" value. For catogorical variables, the result is interpreted by comparing to the baseline group(see next table).

For example, living in the suburb increases the probability of the household falling into Food Dominant group compared to living in the urban area. That means households in the suburb areas are more likely to spend more on food than those live in the cities.

Result Summary

Age of Reference Person: Generally the age of reference person has little effect on household expenditure patterns. But for households with reference people aged over 75, they are very likely to be in the Housing Dominant group, which means they tend to spend more on housing compared to other households.

Composition of Earners: This one has little effect on household expenditure patterns.

Family Composition: The more members aged over 16, the more likely the households have higher spendings on food. The number of old people in the households has negative effect on transportaion expenditures, while the number of adults has positive effect.

Highest Education: Compared to the lowest education level one, a higher degree household tends to spend more on housing instead of food.

Housing Tenure: Compared to households living in owned houses with mortgage, households renting houses spend more on housing. Households without housing mortgage or not renting are more likely to have higher expenditre on food and transportation. For students in student housing, they spend more on food in percentage compared to other groups.

Income Class: Households with income ranging from 15,000 to 5,0000 dollars are more likely to spend on housing and transportation compared to the lowest income class families.

Race of Reference Person: The race has effect on the expenditure patterns.

Region: Households living in the rural area have higher chances to spend more on food and transportation compared to those living in the urban area.

Conclusion¶

Companies can target on the corresponding household cluster based on their services to maximize their profits. We provide a general guideline here.

Housing service companies can target on households in middle income class, higher eudcation level, living in rented house and in the urban area.

Food service companies can focus on households with low income, lower education level, living in owned house and in the rural area, and students.

Transportation service companies can look for housholds with younger age composition, higher education level and living in the urban area.
